              <section class="prose mt-6">
                <h2>Roman numerals vs. Roman units – two different systems</h2>
                <p>
                  Modern websites often focus either on <strong>Roman numerals</strong> or on
                  <strong>Roman measures</strong>. This page brings both worlds together: in the first tab you can
                  convert numerals such as <code>MMXXV</code> to their decimal counterparts, while the second tab
                  focuses on historical length, volume and weight units used throughout the Roman Empire.
                </p>

                <h3>Key assumptions behind the Roman units</h3>
                <p>
                  Ancient standards were not perfectly uniform across provinces or periods. To make the converter
                  practical and consistent, we adopt widely cited modern approximations:
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>Roman foot (pes):</strong> 0.296&nbsp;m</li>
                  <li><strong>Roman mile (mille passus):</strong> 1,000&nbsp;paces = 1,480&nbsp;m</li>
                  <li><strong>Amphora quadrantal:</strong> about 26&nbsp;L</li>
                  <li><strong>Sextarius:</strong> 1/48 of an amphora (≈ 0.54&nbsp;L)</li>
                  <li><strong>Roman pound (libra):</strong> about 329&nbsp;g</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  These values are close enough for courses in history, archaeology and engineering, and they keep
                  internal ratios between Roman units exactly consistent.
                </p>

                <h3>How Roman numerals are interpreted</h3>
                <p>
                  The numerals converter follows standard textbook rules:
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Valid symbols: I, V, X, L, C, D, M.</li>
                  <li>Subtractive notation allowed only for I before V or X, X before L or C, C before D or M.</li>
                  <li>Repeated symbols limited to three in a row (e.g. III is valid, IIII is flagged).</li>
                  <li>Supported range: 1 to 3999 (I to MMMCMXCIX).</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  If you enter a malformed numeral, the tool will show an error message rather than silently returning
                  an incorrect value.
                </p>

                <h2 id="faq">FAQ: Roman units and this converter</h2>

                <h3>Can I rely on these numbers in scientific work?</h3>
                <p>
                  For high-level comparisons, teaching and exploratory calculations, yes. For original research on
                  Roman metrology you should always quote the specific reconstruction (museum artefact, inscription or
                  scholarly article) that motivates the values you use.
                </p>

                <h3>Why does the Roman mile differ from the modern mile?</h3>
                <p>
                  The modern statute mile is about 1.609&nbsp;km; the Roman mile is shorter at around 1.48&nbsp;km
                  because it is built from Roman feet, which are slightly shorter than modern imperial feet, and uses
                  1,000 paces as its definition.
                </p>

                <h3>How precise are the litre and gram conversions?</h3>
                <p>
                  Internally the calculator keeps more decimal digits than it displays. The main source of uncertainty
                  is historical, not numerical: different authors give slightly different reconstructions. Those
                  differences are typically within a few percent.
